    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\nKeys valid in `CTRL-X` mode are never mapped while insert completion is active, so `<C-n>`/`<C-p>` cannot be remapped for completion started by `complete()`, e.g. by `vim.lsp.completion`.\r\n\r\nIn particular, this doesn't work as expected:\r\n\r\n```vim\r\ninoremap <expr> <C-n> pumvisible() ? \"\\<Down>\" : \"\\<C-n>\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nSee #9905 for more discussion.\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nDo not disable mappings in `CTRL_X_EVAL` mode (completion started by `complete()`).  This shouldn't cause any problems because in this mode, mappings cannot interfere with selecting the completion method, which is I think what the no-mapping rule exists for (`:map <C-F> <C-X><C-F>`).\r\n\r\nThis is technically a breaking change because anyone who had `inoremap <C-n>` set, will have this mapping now also applied during completions. But this breaking is limited to `complete()`-started completions.\r\n\r\n## Alternative: apply mappings during any active completion\r\n\r\nA more general fix would apply mappings during *any* active completion, including the CTRL-X submodes (`<C-x><C-o>` etc., which is the vim/vim#6440 case), by gating the no-mapping rule on \"completion method still being selected\" instead (`!ins_compl_active()`, plus an exemption for `CTRL_X_CMDLINE_CTRL_X` where `compl_started` stays true while the next key still selects a method). That is arguably more consistent and less surprising — one rule: \"once completion is active, keys are mapped\", but might be more of a breaking change.\r\n\r\nNote that I previously also suggested another solution to this problem: #34455",
    "closed_at": "2026-06-13T21:45:44Z",
