            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The example is wrong. `pumvisible()` is true for any pum, but this PR only maps keys when completion was started by `complete()` eval mode. With other ins-completion mode  the pum is also visible but the mapping won't fire, so `pumvisible()` can't tell the two cases apart, and this example is misleading. I think it should be \r\n```vim\r\ninoremap <expr> <C-N> complete_info().mode ==# 'eval' ? '<Down>' : '<C-N>'\r\n```\r\n\r\nAnd this is specific to complete(), so it should be placed in the complete() description. Is there any reason not to try this PR on Vim?\r\n\r\nAlso https://github.com/vim/vim/issues/16880 \r\n",
            "commit_id": "3ce5f6f28315d4919c75c3a455da853a5ae3f794",
            "created_at": "2026-06-11T02:41:51Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -671,8 +671,11 @@ When the popup menu is displayed there are a few more special keys, see\n \n Note: The keys that are valid in CTRL-X mode are not mapped.  This allows for\n `:map <C-F> <C-X><C-F>` to work.  The key that ends CTRL-X mode (any key that\n-is not a valid CTRL-X mode command) is mapped. Also, when doing completion\n-with 'complete' mappings apply as usual.\n+is not a valid CTRL-X mode command) is mapped.  Also, mappings apply as usual\n+when doing completion with 'complete' or when completion was started with\n+|complete()| (the latter differs from Vim).  For example, this works during\n+completion started by complete(): >vim\n+    inoremap <expr> <C-N> pumvisible() ? '<Down>' : '<C-N>'",
